Mills looks into how MDG 5 has been implemented in Mexico, how it has been experienced by individuals and groups, what obstacles have been encountered, and what factors have facilitated improvements in maternal health. Using data gathered from interviews with NGOs, government officials, and health care workers, the book argues that government and feminist NGO efforts to build trust in the health care system have fallen short because of systemic failures to protect women’s rights and enhance the quality of health care. In Mexico a woman’s risk of dying from a pregnancy-related complication is five times higher than in developed countries. The Limits of Trust explores the realities of implementing maternal health initiatives on the ground in rural, remote, and impoverished areas, and the steps that can be taken to successfully combat maternal mortality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMaternal health serviceszMexico. 0aMedical policyzMexico. 0aMothersxMortalityzMexicoxPrevention. 0aPregnancyxComplicationszMexico. 0aPregnant womenxServices forzMexico. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh1 aMills, Lisa Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780773552500?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773552500423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773552500/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles